To solve this system of linear equations, we can use the method of substitution or elimination. In this case, we will use the elimination method.

First, let's multiply the first equation by 2 and the second equation by 1 to make the coefficients of x in both equations equal:

\begin{align*} 2(x+2y-3z)&=2(4+2i) \\ 1(2x-y+5z)&=1(3-i) \end{align*}

Which gives us:

\begin{align*} 2x+4y-6z&=8+4i \\ 2x-y+5z&=3-i \end{align*}

Now, subtract the second equation from the first equation:

\begin{align*} (2x+4y-6z)-(2x-y+5z)&=(8+4i)-(3-i) \\ 5y-11z&=5+3i \end{align*}

Next, multiply the first equation by 3 and the third equation by 1 to make the coefficients of x in both equations equal:

\begin{align*} 3(x+2y-3z)&=3(4+2i) \\ 1(3x+4y-2z)&=1(8+5i) \end{align*}

Which gives us:

\begin{align*} 3x+6y-9z&=12+6i \\ 3x+4y-2z&=8+5i \end{align*}

Now, subtract the third equation from the first equation:

\begin{align*} (3x+6y-9z)-(3x+4y-2z)&=(12+6i)-(8+5i) \\ 2y-7z&=4+i \end{align*}

Now we have two equations with two variables:

\begin{align*} 5y-11z&=5+3i \\ 2y-7z&=4+i \end{align*}

Multiply the second equation by 5/2 to make the coefficients of y equal:

\begin{align*} 5y-11z&=5+3i \\ \frac{5}{2}(2y-7z)&=\frac{5}{2}(4+i) \end{align*}

Which gives us:

\begin{align*} 5y-11z&=5+3i \\ 5y-17.5z&=10+2.5i \end{align*}

Now, subtract the first equation from the second equation:

\begin{align*} (5y-17.5z)-(5y-11z)&=(10+2.5i)-(5+3i) \\ -6.5z&=5-0.5i \end{align*}

Now, divide both sides by -6.5 to find z:

\begin{align*} z&=\frac{5-0.5i}{-6.5} \end{align*}

Which gives us:

\begin{align*} z&=-\frac{5}{13}+\frac{1}{13}i \end{align*}

Now that we have z, we can find y by substituting z back into one of the equations with y and z. We will use the equation 5y - 11z = 5 + 3i:

\begin{align*} 5y-11(-\frac{5}{13}+\frac{1}{13}i)&=5+3i \end{align*}

Simplify:

\begin{align*} 5y+\frac{55}{13}-\frac{11}{13}i&=5+3i \end{align*}

Subtract 55/13 from both sides:

\begin{align*} 5y-\frac{11}{13}i&=-\frac{10}{13}+3i \end{align*}

Now, divide both sides by 5:

\begin{align*} y&=-\frac{2}{13}+\frac{3}{5}i+\frac{11}{65}i \end{align*}

Which gives us:

\begin{align*} y&=-\frac{2}{13}+\frac{62}{65}i \end{align*}

Finally, we can find x by substituting y and z back into one of the original equations. We will use the equation x + 2y - 3z = 4 + 2i:

\begin{align*} x+2(-\frac{2}{13}+\frac{62}{65}i)-3(-\frac{5}{13}+\frac{1}{13}i)&=4+2i \end{align*}

Simplify:

\begin{align*} x-\frac{4}{13}+\frac{124}{65}i+\frac{15}{13}-\frac{3}{13}i&=4+2i \end{align*}

Combine like terms:

\begin{align*} x+\frac{11}{13}+\frac{121}{65}i&=4+2i \end{align*}

Subtract 11/13 from both sides:

\begin{align*} x+\frac{121}{65}i&=\frac{41}{13}+2i \end{align*}

Now, subtract 121/65i from both sides:

\begin{align*} x&=\frac{41}{13}+2i-\frac{121}{65}i \end{align*}

Which gives us:

\begin{align*} x&=\frac{41}{13}-\frac{51}{65}i \end{align*}

So the solution to the system of linear equations is:

\begin{align*} x&=\frac{41}{13}-\frac{51}{65}i \\ y&=-\frac{2}{13}+\frac{62}{65}i \\ z&=-\frac{5}{13}+\frac{1}{13}i \end{align*}
